# WordPress Security

## Access Control

- Check capabilities (`current_user_can`) before every privileged action.
- Never rely only on hidden fields or UI visibility for authorization.

## CSRF Protection

- Use nonces for any state-changing request.
- Validate nonce with `check_admin_referer` or `check_ajax_referer` depending on context.

## Input Handling

- Treat all external input as untrusted.
- Validate data shape and allowed values before business logic.
- Sanitize input before persisting (`sanitize_text_field`, `sanitize_key`, `absint`, etc.).

## Output Handling

- Escape all dynamic output at render time:
  - `esc_html` for text nodes
  - `esc_attr` for attribute values
  - `esc_url` for URLs
  - `wp_kses_post` only when controlled HTML is allowed

## Database Safety

- Use `$wpdb->prepare()` for dynamic SQL values.
- Avoid direct interpolation of user-controlled data in SQL.
- Keep schema updates through controlled migrations (`dbDelta` when needed).

## Operational Safety

- Do not expose stack traces or sensitive internals to users.
- Keep uninstall cleanup guarded by `WP_UNINSTALL_PLUGIN`.
